nd "up to heaven and down to hell," which means that landowners have the exclusive right to lease their subsurface mineral estates to petroleum companies. Colin Jerolmack spent eight months living with rural communities outside of Williamsport as they confronted the tension between property rights and the commonwealth. In this deeply intimate book, he reveals how the decision to lease brings financial rewards but can also cause irreparable harm to neighbors, to communal resources like air and water, and even to oneself.Up to Heaven and Down to Hell casts America’s ideas about freedom and property rights in a troubling new light, revealing how your personal choices can undermine your neighbors’ liberty, and how the exercise of individual rights can bring unintended environmental consequences for us all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnvironmentalismzPennsylvaniazWilliamsport. 0aGas industryxEnvironmental aspectszPennsylvaniazWilliamsport. 0aHydraulic fracturingxEnvironmental aspectszPennsylvaniazWilliamsport. 0aLandownerszPennsylvaniazWilliamsport. 0aOil and gas leaseszPennsylvaniazWilliamsport. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh  aAmerican politics.  aAppalachia.  aEarthAction.  aGreenpeace.  aMillionaire’s Row.  aResponsible Drilling Alliance.  aclimate change.  aconservatives.  aculture wars.  aenergy independence.  aenvironment.  aenvironmental contamination.  aenvironmental movement.  aenvironmentalism.  aethnography.  afracking pros and cons.  afractivism.  afractivists.  ahydraulic fracturing.  aland use law.  aland use.  aoil dependency.  aoil drilling.  apolarization.  apolitics.  aproperty.  ared states.  aresource dilemmas.  aresource extraction.  arural America.  arustbelt.  asmall-town America.08iTitle is pa